            <article class="layout-article" id="firehose-45391159">
        <header class="story-header">
            
            <h1 id="title-45391159"><a href="//yro-beta.slashdot.org/story/13/04/14/1838217/maintaining-a-publicly-available-blacklist---mechanisms-and-principles">Maintaining a Publicly Available Blacklist - Mechanisms and Principles</a></h1>
            
                <h4>
                    
                    <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~samzenpus" class="author">samzenpus</a> posted  about a year ago  | from the it's-not-me-it's-you dept. 
                    

                    
                </h4>
            
                <span class="topic" id="topic-45391159"> <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/index2.pl?fhfilter=spam" onclick="return addfhfilter('spam');">
            <img src="//c.fsdn.com/s/topics/spam_64.png" width="30px" height="30px" alt="Spam" title="Spam">
        </a></span>
                <a href="//yro-beta.slashdot.org/story/13/04/14/1838217/maintaining-a-publicly-available-blacklist---mechanisms-and-principles"><span class="comment-count">89</span></a>
        </header>
	
            
        <div class="elips" data-link="//yro-beta.slashdot.org/story/13/04/14/1838217/maintaining-a-publicly-available-blacklist---mechanisms-and-principles">
            <p  id="text-45391159">
                    
                        badger.foo writes <i>"When you publicly assert that somebody sent spam, you need to ensure that your data is accurate. Your process needs to be simple and verifiable, and to compensate for any errors, you want your process to be transparent to the public with clear points of contact and line of responsibility. Here are <a href="http://bsdly.blogspot.ca/2013/04/maintaining-publicly-available.html">some pointers</a> from the operator of the bsdly.net greytrap-based blacklist."</i>
                        
                    
            </p>
        </div>
        <footer class="article-footer">
            
        </footer>
	
    </article>
